<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n14194d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14194d">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14194d"> 194(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Babylonian / captivity D</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Domhnall, King of Ireland &hellip; was succeeded by Mealseachlainn, Aulaf Cuaran&apos;s step-son and son-in-law. On this relationship Mealseachlainn possibly founded some claim to the throne of Dublin, and &hellip; laid siege to the city &ldquo;for three days and three nights,&rdquo; and ultimately succeeded in reducing it to subjection. It was then Mealseachlainn issued his famous proclamation, &ldquo;that as many of the Irish nation as lived in servitude and bondage with the Danes &hellip; should presently &hellip; live freely in their own countries according to their wonted manner.&rdquo; The captivity of these unfortunate Irishmen being described in our annals as &ldquo;the <mark>Babylonian captivity of Ireland</mark> (and) until they were released by Mealseachlainn, it was indeed next to the captivity of hell.&rdquo; <small> Charles Haliday, <a name="SKD1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SKD1"><cite title="source">The Scandinavian Kingdom of Dublin</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1884) 80</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
